"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77053","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-09-24","<p> </p><p>In 2010, the previous Administration initiated a review of coalfields regeneration; this was completed in September 2010 and the Government’s response was published in March 2011 – as summarised in the Written Ministerial Statement by my rt. hon. Friend, the Member for Welwyn Hatfield (Grant Shapps), on 10 March 2011, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 74WS. This outlined a four year programme to make the Trust self-financing, and a tapered level of funding. As laid out in that approach, funding to the Trust was £17.7 million in 2010-11, £16 million in 2011-12, £14 million in 2012-13, £12 million in 2013-14 and will be £10 million in 2014-15.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In line with the strategy, the Coalfields Regeneration Trust will no longer receive financial support from DCLG after March 2015, but they have been allowed to invest grant in assets, whilst still adhering to their core objectives of supporting coalfields communities to enable them to generate an income from 2015 onwards. The Trust now has a strong portfolio of investment and an opportunity to concentrate on the areas where they add value.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Homes and Communities Agency’s Coalfields Programme has invested over £660 million in coalfields project. The land assets associated with Coalfields Projects are expected to form part of the Homes and Communities Agency’s upcoming programme to dispose of Public Sector Land.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DCLG’s Coalfields Funds have also been investing in innovative small and medium firms in deprived former coalfields areas and will continue to do so until mid-2016, as per the June 2009 contractual agreement with the Coalfields Growth Fund partnership. As of 30 June 2014 the Funds have invested £16.9 million in total.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><br></p><p>More broadly, the Government’s approach is to provide local leaders, residents and businesses with the powers, flexibilities, options and incentives to put them in the driving seat to regenerate their area, strengthen their local economy, and improve their opportunities.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of its long-term economic plan to secure Britain’s future, the Government has agreed a series of Growth Deals with businesses and local authorities across England which will provide support for local businesses to train young people, create thousands of new jobs, build thousands of new homes and start hundreds of infrastructure projects; including transport improvements and superfast broadband networks. There is a real opportunity for the Local Enterprise Partnerships which cover former coalfield areas to take a major role in taking forward regeneration locally.</p><p> </p><p><em> </em></p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","205109","2014-09-24T15:29:40.6480386Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77053/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77053/answer",,,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-10","Coalfields Regeneration Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if his Department will make an assessment of the implications for its policies of the conclusions and recommendations of the recent report from the Coalfields Regeneration Trust entitled The State of the Coalfields; and whether his Department provides or plans to provide funding for the Coalfields Regeneration Trust.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","205254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-12-18","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement on integration made by my rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State (Eric Pickles) today.</p><p> </p>","Bristol West","Stephen Williams","205039 ; 205041 ; 205262","2014-12-18T15:29:31.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer","Bristol West","Bristol West","Stephen Williams","Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer/previousversion/10391","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer/previousversion/10391","Biography information for Stephen Williams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77054/answer/previousversion/10391","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-07-10","Community Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funds his Department has allocated to community integration or cohesion in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","205263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77055","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-22","<p>Since 2010 the Department has let 5 contracts between £1 million and £3million. These have been for:</p><p> </p><p>• Legal services in respect of Rural Broadband</p><p>• Legal services in respect of the Mobile Infrastructure Project</p><p>• 3 contracts to test the feasibility of rolling out superfast broadband to the hardest to reach areas;</p><p> </p><p>It has also let 4 contracts since 2010 that have been over £3 million. These are:</p><p> </p><p>1. Mobile Infrastructure Project</p><p>2. Taking Part Survey</p><p>3. Contingent Labour</p><p> </p><p>4. In addition, the Department holds the contract for the Broadband Delivery Framework under which the Devolved Administrations and local authorities have contracted to provide superfast broadband as part of the Government’s programme to reach 90% of the UK by early 2016.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is also about to let 1 contract over £3 million for Ceremonial Event Management Services.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold any contract information on contracts let by its agencies.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold data on the amounts spent on monitoring each contract and could only provide it at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of the number of officials monitoring contracts, Broadband Delivery UK (BDUK) is responsible for the Government’s Superfast Broadband Rollout (Rural) Programme to provide superfast broadband to 90% of premises and to universal standard broadband to all by 2016. £1.2m of public funding is being invested in 44 separate local contracts to roll out Phase 1 of this programme; plus £150m in multiple local contracts in 22 cities as part of the Super Connected Cities Programme to provide free wifi in public buildings, transport networks and public spaces and help small business connect to superfast broadband; and the £150m Mobile Infrastructure Project contract to enhance mobile connectivity in areas with no coverage. BDUK has around 90 staff, many of whom are involved in monitoring delivery of these programmes and contracts.</p><p> </p><p>There are approximately 4.5 officials monitoring the other contracts listed.</p><p> </p>","Maidstone and The Weald","Mrs Helen Grant",,"2014-07-22T13:19:12.5415677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77055/answer","Biography information for Mrs Helen Grant","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77055/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many contracts (a) let since 2010 and (b) about to be let by his Department and its agencies are worth (i) between £1 million and £3 million and (ii) over £3 million; how much has been spent on monitoring each contract let by his Department since 2010; and how many officials in his Department monitor each contract let since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","205198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77056","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-17","<p>I am satisfied that the West Yorkshire project is on scheduled to deliver, within the agreed timetable, superfast broadband to nearly 59,000 premises in West Yorkshire by September 2015. The local broadband project team provide information about the roll-out timetable, including a post code checker on the local authority web site, which can be found at <a href="http://www.superfastwestyorkshire.co.uk/coverage" target="_blank">http://www.superfastwestyorkshire.co.uk/coverage</a>. With respect to the Green Lane Industrial Estate, my Department has been informed the local cabinet connecting that site is scheduled to be upgraded to fibre broadband by the end of September 2014.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-17T12:22:09.8072557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77056/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77056/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Broadband: West Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when Superfast West Yorkshire will be (a) finished and (b) ready to use by  businesses in Green Lane Industrial Estate, in Featherstone; and what assessment he has made of the length of time taken to complete this work.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","205110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77057","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-15","<p>I hold regular meetings with supplier Arqiva to discuss the Mobile Infrastructure Project and officials in BDUK are in constant contact with Arqiva to monitor and assess progress.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-15T15:18:20.1346786Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77057/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77057/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of the progress of the Mobile Infrastructure Project.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","205123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77058","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-15","<p>Ofcom compile data on coverage from the mobile network operators to feed into their Infrastructure Report. In March this year Ofcom commissioned updated voice coverage data from the operators to feed into planning for the Mobile Infrastructure Project. This data covers the UK, including Cambridgeshire, and highlights areas with no coverage from any operator, or ‘not spots'. The Mobile Infrastructure Project aims to put in place infrastructure to provide coverage to as many not spots containing premises as possible.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-15T15:19:40.6203945Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77058/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77058/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Mobile Phones: Cambridgeshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what spot data Ofcom holds for Cambridgeshire.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","205124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77059","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-15","<p>The Department does not directly monitor mobile coverage. Ofcom undertakes monitoring of mobile coverage and ensures compliance by the mobile network operators with any coverage obligations included in their spectrum licences. Ofcom's most recent coverage figures, published in December 2013, indicate that 99.8% of premises in Cambridgeshire receive signal from at least one mobile operator, and 89.6% from all four operators.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-15T15:20:23.7936205Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77059/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77059/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Mobile Phones: Cambridgeshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment his Department has made of mobile telephone coverage in Cambridgeshire.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","205125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77060","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-15","<p>Since the Law Commission published its report on the reform of the Electronic Communications Code in February 2013, my Department has been considering the implications of the recommendations on network rollout and service provision to consumers. In January 2014 we published an economic analysis of the impact of various wayleave valuation regimes. A copy of this report has been placed in the House of Commons library. The analysis work is ongoing and I will make public the plans to reform the Electronic Communications Code, and respond to the Law Commission's report, in due course.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-15T15:16:44.6703258Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77060/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77060/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Telecommunications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, when the Government will publish its response to the Law Commission's recommendations for reform of the Electronic Communications Code.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","205121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77061","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-15","<p>The Department does not directly monitor mobile coverage. Ofcom undertakes monitoring of mobile coverage and ensures compliance by the mobile network operators with any coverage obligations included in their spectrum licences. We expect the 4G rollout to be the fastest and most complete rollout in the EU, and this will ensure the UK continues to have some of the best mobile services in Europe.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-15T15:17:29.7805832Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77061/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77061/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","4G","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how his Department is monitoring the roll-out of 4G telephone coverage; and who is conducting that monitoring.","false","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","205122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77062","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-07-17","<p>The annual public library statistics compiled by the Chartered Institute of Public Finance and Accountancy based on information provided by the individual library authorities indicates that the total book stock for public libraries in England at 31 March 2013 was 72.4 million.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-07-17T12:21:25.6256575Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77062/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77062/answer",,,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-07-10","Public Libraries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will estimate the total number of books currently held in public libraries.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77064","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>Of the £64.5 billion referred to in the 2013 Equipment Plan we plan to allocate to the procurement of new equipment, £2.3 billion is for the successor nuclear deterrent programme in the period up to Main Gate in 2016, when a future investment decision will be made. The 2010 Strategic Defence and Security Review determined that a replacement warhead would not be required until at least the late 2030s, meaning a decision to replace the existing warhead will not be required until the next Parliament. In the meantime, we are maintaining the capability at the Atomic Weapons Establishment to design a replacement warhead should that be required. Current forecasts indicate that costs should remain within the 2006 White Paper estimate: £11-14 billion for the submarine and £2-3 billion for the warhead (at 2006 economic conditions).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-21T15:51:56.2553856Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77064/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77064/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Nuclear Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much of the funding allocated in the Defence and Equipment Plan 2013 for the procurement of new equipment will be spent on the successor nuclear deterrent programme and any redesign of the nuclear warhead.","false","Biography information for Angus Robertson","Moray","Angus Robertson","205173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77065","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Air intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and <br>reconnaissance (ISTAR) Optimisation Study (AIOS) is designed to inform decisions on how future Air ISTAR capability, including Maritime Patrol Aircraft, could be delivered. The study is ongoing and activity in the coming months will consider capability requirements and priorities against a range of policy driven scenarios. The AIOS is one of a number of ongoing strands on analysis that will contribute to the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","205175","2014-07-21T15:48:32.7242918Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77065/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77065/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2014, Official Report, column 142, on military aircraft, what the main capabilities are which any future military patrol aircraft will need to possess; whether such capabilities will include (a) surveillance capabilities against (i) sub-surface, (ii) surface and (iii) land targets, (b) attack capabilities against each of those types of targets, (c) command, control and intelligence-gathering capabilities and (d) maritime rescue capabilities; and when a final decision will be taken on the mix of capabilities which will be required on a future maritime patrol aircraft.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","205174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77066","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>The value of equipment and stores written off in 2013-14 as a result of loss or suspected theft will be available once the Ministry of Defence’s 2013-14 Annual Report &amp; Accounts have been laid before Parliament, which is planned for the autumn 2014.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T14:05:52.5043015Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77066/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77066/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Lost Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what Ministry of Defence equipment of what value was recorded as lost or stolen in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77067","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>There has been no external expenditure on media training or social media training for the Secretary of State for Defence or the Ministers in the Department.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T13:46:54.9613112Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77067/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77067/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on what (a) media training and (b) social media training for (i) him and (ii) Ministers in his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77068","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>Consumption of alcohol on Ministry of Defence premises is permitted so long as it does not affect the proper and professional conduct of official business. Acceptable occasions might include receptions or other events held in function rooms, or staff leaving drinks.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T14:30:18.4865758Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77068/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77068/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his Department's policy is on alcohol consumption (a) in general on the premises and (b) during parties in his Private Office.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77069","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2014-07-22T16:22:07.3181634Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77069/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77069/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much has been spent on refurbishing (a) gym and leisure facilities, (b) cafeteria and (c) interior decoration within (i) his Department and (ii) his Department-owned buidlings in (A) 2013 and (B) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77070","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>This information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T14:04:41.3093196Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77070/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77070/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many away days his Department has held for its officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014; and what the cost of each such event has been.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-09-12","<p>Information on individual media subscriptions is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.<br><br>The Ministry Of Defence (MOD) purchases its print and electronic journals through a pan-Government framework contract. Our expenditure against this contract totalled £584,387 (excluding VAT) in financial year 2013-14.<br>The contract is mainly used for the purchase of academic, technical, medical and trade publications for the MOD colleges, training centres, technical information centres and medical units, including those in operational theatres. A small number of recreational titles are provided for use in personnel recovery centres.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-09-12T13:06:26.0908751Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer","Broxtowe","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer/previousversion/11772","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer/previousversion/11772","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77071/answer/previousversion/11772","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Mass Media: Subscriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the annual cost is of each subscription to (a) magazines and (b) television channels held by his Department.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77072","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>Members of the Armed Forces are attached to the Royal Household in order to provide support to the Head of State and manage the extensive involvement and interaction of the Royal Family with the UK military at home and abroad. They also support state ceremonial events and formal, state sponsored, visits by members of the Royal Family. Information on Armed Forces personnel permanently attached to the Royal Household is provided in the table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Service Personnel</p><p>Permanently Attached to</p><p>The Royal Household</p><p> </p></td><td><p>Approximate Cost</p><p>£</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>890,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>950,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p>920,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>800,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T14:31:16.9203823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77072/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77072/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Armed Forces: Royal Household","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many armed forces personnel have been attached to the Royal Household in each year since 2010; and what the cost of such attachments has been.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77073","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>Expenditure on hospitality and entertainment is published in the Notes to the Ministry of Defence’s Annual Report and Accounts each year. We spent £1.527 million on this activity in 2012-13. We estimate that expenditure will be in the same region in 2013-14 and 2014-15. The figure for 2013-14 will be published in the 2013-14 Annual Report and Accounts later this year. This compares with expenditure of £4.3 million in 2008-09 + £3.8 million in 2009-10 under the previous Government. <br><br>We do not hold financial information in a form that allows us to identify expenditure on alcohol separately. This information could therefore be provided only at disproportionate cost. The provision of alcoholic refreshments at public expense is authorised only in exceptional circumstances and must be modest and appropriate in nature.Expenditure on hospitality and entertainment is published in the Notes to the Ministry of Defence’s Annual Report and Accounts each year. We spent £1.527 million on this activity in 2012-13. We estimate that expenditure will be in the same region in 2013-14 and 2014-15. The figure for 2013-14 will be published in the 2013-14 Annual Report and Accounts later this year. This compares with expenditure of £4.3 million in 2008-09 and £3.8 million in 2009-10 under the previous Government. <br><br>We do not hold financial information in a form that allows us to identify expenditure on alcohol separately. This information could therefore be provided only at disproportionate cost. The provision of alcoholic refreshments at public expense is authorised only in exceptional circumstances and must be modest and appropriate in nature.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T13:53:57.9745059Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77073/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77073/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Official Hospitality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on (a) entertainment and (b) the purchase of alcohol in (i) 2012-13 and (ii) 2013-14; and what estimate he has made of such spending in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205058"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77074","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Secretary of State for Defence placed the report in the Library of the House on 15 July 2014.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-07-21T13:50:06.3656333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77074/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77074/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Reserve Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when he plans to publish the Annual Report on Reserve Forces as submitted by the Reserve Forces and Cadets Association.","false","Biography information for Lord Arbuthnot of Edrom","North East Hampshire","Mr James Arbuthnot","205060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77075","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>It is a key requirement for the Armed Forces to maintain a satisfactory balance of skills, experience, ability and seniority in rank to enable delivery of operational requirements. Despite the reduction in overall numbers of Service personnel, the requirement for the Armed Forces to recruit and train personnel to replace those who leave the services remains.</p><p> </p><p>Details of money spent by the Ministry of Defence in financial year (FY) 2013-14 on recruitment advertising for television and on printed materials are included in the table below. This information is broken down by Service and civilian staff.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p> </p><p><strong>Cost of recruitment advertising on television FY 2013-14 (including production costs).</strong></p><p> </p></td><td><p> </p><p><strong>Cost of recruitment advertising on printed materials FY 2013-14 (including careers publications)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Army </strong></p></td><td><p>£1,289,367</p></td><td><p> </p><p>£1,067,547</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Royal Air Force </strong></p></td><td><p>£2,260,086</p></td><td><p> </p><p>£83,077</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Royal Navy </strong></p></td><td><p>£4,447,000</p></td><td><p> </p><p>£400,800</p><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Civilians staff </strong></p></td><td><p>n/a</p></td><td><p> </p><p>£610,891*</p><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* This figure includes the cost of recruitment advertising where the MOD has paid for a media package to advertise in a newspaper and on the publications website.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-07-21T13:49:27.4076112Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77075/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77075/answer",,,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent on recruitment advertising (a) on television and (b) on printed materials in 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-22","<p>The information is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2014-07-22T16:58:17.0081326Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer","Broxtowe","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer/previousversion/11782","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer/previousversion/11782","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77076/answer/previousversion/11782","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many individuals in his Department have participated in (a) disability awareness and (b) LGBT awareness training in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-08-04","<p>To date, £4.3 million of the £10.85 million Cadet Expansion Programme budget has been spent. This represents 40% of the total budget.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2014-08-04T10:16:03.5730339Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer","Broxtowe","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer/previousversion/11778","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer/previousversion/11778","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77077/answer/previousversion/11778","11","Defence","Defence","2014-07-10","Armed Forces: Cadets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the budget for the Cadet Expansion Programme has been spent to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77078","Ministry of Defence","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>The number and types of medals and clasps that have been issued by the Ministry of Defence Medal Office between 1 January 2011 and 31 May 2014 is shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><em>Type of Medal/ Clasp</em></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><em>2011</em></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><em>2012</em></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><em>2013</em></p></td><td colspan="2"><p><em>2014</em></p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p><em>Medals</em></p></td><td><p><em>Clasps</em></p></td><td><p><em>Medals</em></p></td><td><p><em>Clasps</em></p></td><td><p><em>Medals</em></p></td><td><p><em>Clasps</em></p></td><td><p><em>Medals</em></p></td><td><p><em>Clasps</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Historic (First World War)</p></td><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>17</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Historic (Second World War)</p></td><td><p>8,600</p></td><td><p>256</p></td><td><p>8,307</p></td><td><p>346</p></td><td><p>8,595</p></td><td><p>315</p></td><td><p>5,149</p></td><td><p>182</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Post War Campaigns</p></td><td><p>2,223</p></td><td><p>131</p></td><td><p>1,707</p></td><td><p>99</p></td><td><p>1,542</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>895</p></td><td><p>75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Current</p></td><td><p>17,990</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>19,096</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>13,752</p></td><td><p>122</p></td><td><p>5,817</p></td><td><p>76</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Conduct and Reserves</p></td><td><p>5,177</p></td><td><p>2,332</p></td><td><p>5,116</p></td><td><p>2,173</p></td><td><p>5,237</p></td><td><p>2,181</p></td><td><p>2,645</p></td><td><p>1,365</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Elizabeth Cross</p></td><td><p>463</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>279</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>31</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Honours and Aw