"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77174","Home Office","false","2014-08-04","<p>Published figures on people detained in the United Kingdom solely under Immigration Act powers include those held in short term holding facilities, pre departure accommodation and immigration removal centres. Figures exclude those held in police cells, Prison Service establishments, short term holding rooms at ports and airports (for less than 24 hours), and those recorded as detained under both criminal and immigration powers and their dependants. The following table shows the number of female detainees who had claimed asylum at some point, by reason for leaving detention and by length of detention for each of the last three years.</p><p>The Home Office publishes quarterly and annual statistics on the number of people detained in the United Kingdom for immigration purposes, within Immigration Statistics: January – March 2014, from the GOV.UK website: <br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/home-office/series/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a>.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-08-04T15:22:28.2424525Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77174/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77174/answer","PQ 205112 Table.xlsx","PQ 205112 Table.xlsx","Female detainees","Female detainees","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77174/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Asylum: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the outcomes of detention by length of detention for women asylum seekers detained by her Department were in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","205112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77175","Home Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>On 12 June 2014, the Home Secretary announced to the House that an operational <br>review would be undertaken to ensure that Her Majesty's Passport Office works as efficiently <br>as possible, with better processes, better customer services and better outcomes.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-17T14:40:21.0140504Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77175/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77175/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","HM Passport Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to increase the consistency of information issued by HM Passport Office staff.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","205104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77176","Home Office","false","2014-07-29","<p> </p><p> </p><p>(i) Police Officers must observe the requirements of the Codes of Practice under the Police &amp; Criminal Evidence Act 1984 governing the removal of <br>headgear. A copy of which is available in the House of Commons Library.<br><br>(ii) All passengers wearing a veil or face covering on arrival in the United Kingdom will be asked to remove their veil so that their appearance can be <br>compared with the photograph in their passport, in order that the Border Force officer can be satisfied as to their identity and nationality.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-29T13:18:28.3036997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77176/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77176/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Clothing: Islam","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her policy is on the wearing of (a) the niqab and (b) the burka by individuals during any official interaction with (i) police officers and (ii) immigration officers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77177","Home Office","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>The following table contains the requested data for the change in police <br>officers, special constables, police community support officers and police <br>staff in the Cumbria Constabulary force area since 2010.<br><br>The Home Office does not collect figures for the Westmorland and Lonsdale <br>constituency.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-15T15:34:22.278673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77177/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77177/answer","PQ205055 -table.xlsx","PQ205055 -table.xlsx","Requested data for the change in police officers","Requested data for the change in police officers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77177/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Police: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what changes there have been in the numbers of (a) police officers, (b) special constables, (c) police community support officers and (d) police staff in (i) Westmorland and Lonsdale constituency and (ii) Cumbria Constabulary force area since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","205055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77178","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p>All frontline immigration officials must undertake a mandatory two stage e-learning training package on identifying victims of trafficking. They must also undertake training on safeguarding children. <br><br>The Home Office continuously reviews the training provided to front line officers to ensure that it remains relevant and up to date.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T16:38:38.8033284Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77178/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77178/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Human Trafficking: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what training her Department provides to immigration officials in Northern Ireland to identify victims of human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","205143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77179","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p>The accommodation of unaccompanied asylum seeking children in Northern Ireland is arranged and monitored by the local authority responsible for that child and Social Services maintain an ongoing responsibility for their welfare.<br><br>The Home Office will make social services aware of a child’s arrival at the earliest opportunity. From that point onwards, a variety of professionals will have involvement with the welfare of the child. <br><br>For consideration of their asylum application, children are interviewed by a specially trained decision maker. At the interview, the child will be accompanied by a Responsible Adult. A legal representative would normally be present for the interview and an interpreter if appropriate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T16:42:16.5471455Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77179/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77179/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Asylum: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what facilities are available for unaccompanied children applying for asylum in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","205144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77180","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p>Accommodation is provided for single applicants in single self contained properties and in HMO’s (houses of multiple occupation). Family accommodation is provided for families. Where a service user has specific needs, that impact on the type of accommodation required (e.g. pregnant women), details will be made known to the providers at the time of dispersal to ensure that suitable properties are offered.<br><br>Accommodation for asylum seekers is provided under the COMPASS contract. COMPASS contract providers are required to provide safe, habitable, fit for purpose and correctly equipped accommodation to comply with relevant mandatory and statutory requirements in relation to housing and this includes the Housing Act 2004. Properties are inspected at least once every month.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T16:36:19.1589769Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77180/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77180/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Compass Contracts: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what residential facilities are available in Northern Ireland for asylum applicants; and when those facilities were last inspected.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","205142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p>It is not possible to provide data on the number of claims for asylum that have been received in Northern Ireland since 2010. This information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.<br><br>It is possible to provide an estimated figure for the number of asylum seekers that are recorded as being resident in Northern Ireland during the period specified. This information is provided in the following table.<br><br>These figures relate to main asylum claimants who have made a claim for asylum between 1st January 2010 and 31st March 2014 and who have a latest postcode recorded as located in Northern Ireland. <br><br>The figures quoted have been derived from management information and are therefore provisional and subject to change. This information has not been quality assured under National Statistics protocols.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year of Application</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of Applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>147</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>196</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>235</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014 (Jan - Mar)</p></td><td><p>62</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-21T14:45:30.2047298Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer/previousversion/10307","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer/previousversion/10307","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77181/answer/previousversion/10307","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Asylum: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for asylum were received in Northern Ireland in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","205167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77182","Home Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The Home Secretary announced to the House on 12 June 2014 that people who need <br>to travel within the next seven days and who have waited more than the three <br>weeks standard processing time for straight-forward passport renewals through <br>no fault of their own, will have their application fast tracked at no extra cost.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-17T14:39:33.2199648Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77182/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77182/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether people who urgently need to travel within seven days are charged for upgrading their passport application.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","205199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183","Home Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>As my Right Honourable Friend, the Home Secretary, made clear in the statement <br>made to the House on 10 July, Official Report, columns 456-459, communications <br>data is an absolutely fundamental tool in the investigation of serious crime. <br>The Crown Prosecution Service Organised Crime Division has indicated that <br>communications data plays a role in 95% of the serious and organised crime <br>cases that they handle. An Association of Chief Police Officers' survey from <br>2012 demonstrated the wide range of serious crime types that communications <br>data is used to investigate, including terrorism, drugs trafficking and child <br>abuse. Total crime figures, recorded by the police, and including breakdowns <br>by crime type, can be found on the Office for National Statistics website.<br><br>Law enforcement agencies do not routinely make a record of all of the <br>investigatory techniques that they use when investigating individual crimes, as <br>there is no operational reason to do so. However, Keith Bristow, Director <br>General of the National Crime Agency, made clear in his speech to the Police <br>Foundation on 24 June that communications data is most commonly used in the <br>investigation of the most serious offences, such as murder, rape and kidnap, <br>and that communications data is overwhelmingly the most powerful tool available <br>to those investigating child sexual exploitation.</p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2014-07-17T14:15:10.6681426Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer/previousversion/10283","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer/previousversion/10283","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77183/answer/previousversion/10283","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many serious crimes were solved by communications data since 2010; what the classification of those crimes was; and how many serious crimes there were in that period.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","205171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77184","Home Office","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>UK Border Agency (UKBA) was responsible for customs functions until March 2012. <br>Detection and intelligence work on illegal commodities, including illegal <br>tobacco, is now carried out by Border Force, in partnership with Civil Service <br>and law enforcement colleagues.<br>As operations undertaken by UKBA and Border Force targeted a range of <br>commodities, the numbers of staff working specifically on the tobacco strategy <br>are not available. To release more general information about the numbers of <br>staff involved in such operations would jeopardise the effectiveness of our <br>current customs activities. Border Security must be our prime consideration.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-15T13:24:36.463148Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77184/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77184/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many staff in the UK Border Agency were assigned to implementing the tackling tobacco smuggling strategy in (a) 2011-12 and (b) 2012-13; and how many such staff were engaged in (i) detection, (ii) intelligence gathering and analysis, (iii) investigations and (iv) the provision of legal advice.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","205202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p> </p><p>The Home Office is working with policing and criminal justice partners to review those remaining circumstances where current legislation treats 17 year olds as adults while in police custody.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-21T14:15:45.0388414Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer/previousversion/10297","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer/previousversion/10297","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77185/answer/previousversion/10297","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Young Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 21 October 2013, Official Report, column 65W, on young offenders, if she will bring forward legislative proposals to redefine juveniles to include those older than 16.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","205267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p>The Home Office has taken steps to ensure that it complies fully with the Hughes-Chang court judgement. Mandatory changes have been made to the Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 Codes of Practice C and H, which came into effect in October 2013, which require the police to provide 17 year olds with an appropriate adult and to inform their parents of their detention.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-21T14:19:33.2268544Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer/previousversion/10300","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer/previousversion/10300","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77186/answer/previousversion/10300","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Hughes Chang","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she has taken fully to comply with the High Court judgment in the Hughes Chang case.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","205268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187","Home Office","false","2014-07-21","<p> </p><p> </p><p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2014-07-21T14:21:19.0640112Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer","Hemel Hempstead","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer/previousversion/10306","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer/previousversion/10306","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77187/answer/previousversion/10306","1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Police Custody: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many 17 year olds were held in police custody in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","205269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77188","Home Office","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>Details of staffing resources deployed to specifically deal with tobacco <br>smuggling were not kept, so we are unable to provide information as to the <br>salary costs.<br>In order to ensure the effectiveness of our current operations and maintain <br>border security, Border Force is unable to provide information on the numbers <br>of staff involved in any current or historical operations. Border Security must <br>be our prime consideration.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2014-07-15T13:21:24.38012Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77188/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77188/answer",,,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-07-10","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the cost to her Department of salaries for staff allocated to the tackling tobacco smuggling strategy for those staff (a) engaged in detection, (b) engaged in investigations, (c) working on intelligence matters and (d) in total in (i) 2011-12 and (ii) 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","205204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-22","<p>There are around 800 third party suppliers of services to the House of Commons and given system changes in recent years it would involve disproportionate cost to derive precise figures of contract expenditure by financial year. It is estimated that expenditure has broadly been equivalent to:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Amount (£m)</p></td><td><p>Proportion of spend (%)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>92.7</p></td><td><p>32.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>87.4</p></td><td><p>47.4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>90.7</p></td><td><p>43.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>89.0</p></td><td><p>40.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>83.7</p></td><td><p>37.0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>For 2014/15 the planned amount is around £100 million which represents 40.8% of the combined capital and resource budget.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-22T15:55:12.0665271Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso","John Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer/previousversion/11070","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer/previousversion/11070","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77189/answer/previousversion/11070","18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, how much and what proportion of the House of Commons Commission's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of the House of Commons Commission's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77190","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-16","<p>No specific budget has been allocated for the payment of travel, hotel or subsistence expenses for candidates interviewed for the role of Clerk of the House and Chief Executive. The cost incurred to 14 July is £2,702.31. The costs are met from the House Service's general recruitment budget.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-16T15:21:46.0527385Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77190/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77190/answer",,,,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-10","Clerk of the House","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, what funding the Commission allocated for payment of travel, hotel and subsistence expenses of candidates interviewed for the role of Clerk of the House and Chief Executive; what the actual cost was of paying those expenses; and from which budget those expenses will be paid.","false","Biography information for Sir Simon Burns","Chelmsford","Mr Simon Burns","205043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77191","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-15","<p>The Clerk of the House is the line manager of the other executive members of the Management Board. As part of the House Service's policy of making the work of the House better known to the public, the Clerk encourages members of the Management Board to speak about their work, while of course observing necessary requirements of impartiality and confidentiality, and avoiding any conflicts of interest. Accordingly, within those guidelines, he has given discretion to members of the Board to accept invitations to speak as they see fit and does not require them to seek authorisation for the contents of their remarks or for lines to take.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-15T16:27:22.1815196Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77191/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77191/answer",,,,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-10","House of Commons Board of Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, whether members of the Management Board must seek authorisation for the contents of their remarks or lines to take during oral question and answer sessions at external speaking engagements related to their professional role.","false","Biography information for Thomas Docherty","Dunfermline and West Fife","Thomas Docherty","205004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77192","House of Commons Commission","false","2014-07-15","<p>The House Service does not collect the information requested. As part of the House Service's policy of making the work of the House better known to the public, the Clerk encourages members of the Management Board to speak about their work, and they do so frequently, for example at outreach events.</p>","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","John Thurso",,"2014-07-15T16:29:49.8515218Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77192/answer","Biography information for Viscount Thurso","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77192/answer",,,,,,,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2014-07-10","House of Commons Board of Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross representing the House of Commons Commission, on how many occasions each member of the Management Board has undertaken an external speaking engagement in each of the last four financial years.","false","Biography information for Thomas Docherty","Dunfermline and West Fife","Thomas Docherty","205005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77193","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The Bost Airfield and Agri-Business Park project comprised two separate components. On the airfield upgrade component, DFID worked closely with the Ministry of Transport and Civil Aviation, which operates airfields and airports in Afghanistan, to complete the upgrade. All works have now been handed over to the relevant authorities.</p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T16:07:11.413537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77193/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77193/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Afghanistan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 11 June 2014, Official Report, column 181W, on Afghanistan, for what reason her Department did not engage with the Afghan Investment Support Agency on the Bost airfield project.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","205006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77194","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>Information on the number of DFID away days and the costs incurred is not held centrally and precise information is not readily available.</p><p> </p><p>Away days for Department for International Development (DFID) staff are overwhelmingly undertaken on DFID or Other Government Department premises where there is little or no cost involved.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:28:13.5231636Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77194/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77194/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many away days her Department has held for its officials in (a) 2013 and (b) 2014 to date; and what the cost of each such event has been.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77195","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>Under this Government's transparency programme, contracts and future contract pipeline information is published on Contracts Finder which is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/contracts-finder</a></p><p> </p><p>In regards to the proportion of my Departments contracted spends to overall budget, full copies of the annual accounts are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=annual+accounts&amp;publication_filter_option=corporate-reports&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-international-development&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=annual+accounts&amp;publication_filter_option=corporate-reports&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-international-development&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date=&amp;commit=Refresh+results</a></p><p><br><br></p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2014-07-17T14:29:24.9678504Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77195/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77195/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much and what proportion of her Department's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of her Department's budget she expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77196","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>No refurbishment was made to facilities in 2014.</p><p>The East Kilbride office carried out refurbishment to facilities mentioned at a cost of £5,790 during 2013.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:27:36.8028705Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77196/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77196/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much has been spent on refurbishing (a) gymnasium and leisure facilities, (b) cafeteria and (c) interior decoration within (i) her Department and (ii) buildings owned by her Department in (A) 2013 and (B) 2014 to date.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77197","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>DFID's communications team subscribes to following magazines:</p><p>The Economist: £136 per annum</p><p>The Spectator: £129 per annum</p><p>The New Statesman: £92 per annum</p><p>The New Scientist: £149 per annum</p><p>Private Eye: £28 per annum</p><p>Marketing Magazine: £155 per annum</p><p>PR Week: £99.50 per annum</p><p>PR Week Global: £119.50 per annum</p><p>A figure for magazine subscriptions across the entire Department cannot be compiled from our accounting records without incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p>Television channels are paid for via the Parliamentary feed. DFID pays £6,728.90 each year for maintenance of the Parliamentary TV system and £13,500 a year for rental of the telecomms link from 22 Whitehall to the Palace of Westminster.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:34:55.2356923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77197/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77197/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Mass Media: Subscriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what subscriptions to (a) magazines and (b) television channels her Department funds; and what the annual cost is of each of those subscriptions.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77198","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>DFID operates a decentralised Learning and Development system and does not hold central records of course attendance or small scale expenditure. DFID publishes all expenditure over £500, which can be found on our website http://www.dfid.gov.uk/About-us/How-we-measure-progress/DFID-spend/. Producing any other type of report would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:32:09.5785589Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77198/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77198/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has spent on (a) media training and (b) social media training for (i) her and (ii) other Ministers in her Department; and what specific training was provided in each such case.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77199","Department for International Development","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>I refer Hon. Member to the answer provided today by my Rt Hon. Friend the member for Horsham (Mr Maude).</p><p> </p>","Hornsey and Wood Green","Lynne Featherstone",,"2014-07-17T14:31:40.0561789Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77199/answer","Biography information for Baroness Featherstone","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77199/answer",,,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-07-10","Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her Department's policy is on the consumption of alcohol during social occasions held in her private office.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","205241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77200","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-17","<p>The date for the publication of the proposed consultation paper on the possible creation of a status of guardian of the property and affairs of missing persons has not yet been set but it remains the Government's intention to publish the paper before the end of August (see my Written Ministerial Statement of 8 April 2014 (<em>House of Commons Official Record 8 April 2014 col 8WS</em>)).</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-17T15:06:29.7481296Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77200/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77200/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Missing Persons: Guardianship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to launch his consultation on guardianship for missing people.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Huppert","Cambridge","Dr Julian Huppert","205266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77201","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>There will always be enough prison places for those sent to prison by the courts and the government continues to modernise the prison estate so that it delivers best value for the taxpayer. This Government has a long term strategy for managing the prison estate which will provide more adult male prison capacity than we inherited from the previous Government.</p><p> </p><p>The average rate of crowding is published in the National Offender Management Service Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the 10 years 2004-05 to 2013-14 are set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average Rate of Crowding</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2004-05</strong></p></td><td><p>24.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2005-06</strong></p></td><td><p>24.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2006-07</strong></p></td><td><p>24.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2007-08</strong></p></td><td><p>25.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2008-09</strong></p></td><td><p>24.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009-10</strong></p></td><td><p>24.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010-11</strong></p></td><td><p>23.8%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011-12</strong></p></td><td><p>24.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012-13</strong></p></td><td><p>23.3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>22.9%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In 2013-14, the average number of prisoners held in crowded conditions decreased to 22.9% of the total population compared to 23.3% in 2012-13. This is the lowest level since 2001-02 and has come down from a high of 25.3% in 2007-08.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T13:08:58.7484465Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77201/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77201/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Prisons: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the level of overcrowding was on the Prison Estate in England and Wales in each of the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","205255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77202","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>An indeterminate sentence prisoner will be transferred to open conditions only upon a positive recommendation from the independent Parole Board following a full risk assessment or, exceptionally, without a recommendation from the Parole Board where a prisoner can show exceptional progress. The Justice Secretary recently announced that any prisoner with an abscond history on their current sentence will not be eligible for return to open conditions other than in wholly exceptional circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the National Offender Management Service records the number of indeterminate sentence prisoners transferred into open conditions each year, its case management systems do not report on the total number of indeterminate sentence prisoners who spend time in open conditions in the course of a calendar year; neither do they provide data on the average, maximum and minimum time they spend in open conditions. In order to provide this information, officials would be required to undertake a manual interrogation of case management systems. Such an exercise would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","205145","2014-07-21T13:18:21.0123009Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77202/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77202/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Open Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the (a) average, (b) maximum and (c) minimum time spent in an open prison was for indeterminate sentence prisoners before their release in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77203","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>Prison numbers fluctuate throughout the yearand we have sufficient accommodation for the current and expected population</p><p> </p><p>Sensible measures have been taken to ensure that we will have sufficient capacity to deal with the projected level of the population. These measures include identifying additional places in prisons that can provide safe and decent conditions if required. This is a proportionate measure to ensure that we are able to hold all of those committed to custody by the courts.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions on the number of such spaces required and the effect this will have on each prison’s certified normal accommodation and operational capacity will depend on the current and projected prison population, including an assessment of the necessary margin to manage population fluctuations.</p><p> </p><p>Individual prison population and capacity information for every prison in England and Wales is published monthly on the Ministry of Justice website at: <a title="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/prison-population-figures-2014" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/prison-population-figures-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/prison-population-figures-2014</a></p><p> </p><p>We will end this Parliament with more adult male prison places than we inherited, more hours of work in prisons than we inherited, more education for young detainees than we inherited and a more modern, cost effective prison estate than we inherited.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T11:12:49.8120785Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77203/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77203/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Prison Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the certified normal accommodation and operational capacity is planned to be for each prison establishment on 29 August 2014.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","205260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77204","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Ministry of Justice publishes prison population projections annually as a National Statistic. The publication date for Prison Population Projections 2014–2020 is 27 November 2014.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T12:56:05.68322Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77204/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77204/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans his Department has to publish revised prison population projections.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","205259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77205","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-22","<p>The National Offender Management Service is subject to review throughout the year to address additional expenditure as part of regular budget discussions.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-07-22T16:28:26.2898026Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77205/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77205/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","National Offender Management Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether his Department has allocated additional financial resources to the New Offender Management Service to provide safe conditions for offenders following the recent increase in the prison population.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","205261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77206","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>An indeterminate sentence prisoner will be transferred to open conditions only upon a positive recommendation from the independent Parole Board following a full risk assessment or, exceptionally, without a recommendation from the Parole Board where a prisoner can show exceptional progress. The Justice Secretary recently announced that any prisoner with an abscond history on their current sentence will not be eligible for return to open conditions other than in wholly exceptional circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the National Offender Management Service records the number of indeterminate sentence prisoners transferred into open conditions each year, its case management systems do not report on the total number of indeterminate sentence prisoners who spend time in open conditions in the course of a calendar year; neither do they provide data on the average, maximum and minimum time they spend in open conditions. In order to provide this information, officials would be required to undertake a manual interrogation of case management systems. Such an exercise would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","205150","2014-07-21T13:18:20.9185589Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77206/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77206/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Open Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many indeterminate sentence prisoners have spent time in open prisons in the year ending 31 March (a) 2012, (b) 2013 and (c) 2014.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77207","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-17","<p>The information requested is held by the Legal Aid Agency, but will take time to extract in the form requested. I will write to the Hon Member providing the information as soon as the data can be gathered.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-17T08:37:41.0170185Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77207/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77207/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Legal Aid Scheme: Nottinghamshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people received legal aid in each constituency in Nottinghamshire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","205152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77208","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>To answer either part of this question it is necessary to look at the record of every prisoner who has been in an open prison and either absconded or breached prison disciplinary regulations in the last five years, in order to identify the date of transfer to open conditions and make a calculation. This could only be achieved at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for the number of absconds, by prison, since 1995 are provided in the Prison Digest contained in the Prison and Probation Trusts Performance Statistics. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225234/prison-performance-digest-12-13.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/225234/prison-performance-digest-12-13.xls</a></p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T13:05:48.1667282Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77208/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77208/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Open Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the least amount of time spent in an open prison by a prisoner was before (a) absconding and (b) breaching prison regulations in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77209","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>The Table below shows the amount and proportion of the department’s budget <em>spent on activities which were contracted out. We expect 2014/15 to follow the recent trends. </em></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£3,011,688,897</p></td><td><p>£2,762,309,003</p></td><td><p>£2,514,513,933</p></td><td><p>£2,371,593,459</p></td><td><p>£2,301,260,824</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>40.50%</p></td><td><p>42.04%</p></td><td><p>40.24%</p></td><td><p>38.55%</p></td><td><p>39.19%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T13:12:59.7697539Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77209/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77209/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much and what proportion of his Department's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of his Department's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77210","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-01","<p>There are a number of court orders which may result in the electronic tagging of individuals. Whilst the law allows the electronic monitoring of compliance with these orders, at present it is primarily imposed to monitor compliance with curfew requirements.</p><p> </p><p>Sentencing in individual cases is a matter for the courts, taking into account the circumstances of each case and imposing a sentence which is proportionate to the seriousness of the offence.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-09-01T14:10:45.4753673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77210/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77210/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what his policy is on increasing the number of people tagged as a condition of a court order and supervised by community rehabilitation companies or successor bodies.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","205127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77211","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-01","<p>The Parole Board is an independent body with the statutory power to direct the release of recalled prisoners, indeterminate sentence prisoners whose tariff has expired and those determinate sentence prisoners who are subject to discretionary release arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>Once the Parole Board has directed release, the Secretary of State must give effect to the direction. Exceptionally, the Secretary of State can apply to the High Court to have a Parole Board release direction quashed if he considered it to be irrational although to date he has not sought to do so.</p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-09-01T07:48:58.966128Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77211/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77211/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Parole","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he last intervened in a decision taken by a parole board; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","204994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77212","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-17","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The sentencing framework applies to all offenders who appear before the courts regardless of gender. The courts must however have regard to the individual circumstances of the offence and the offender. Offenders who commit serious offences face lengthy custodial sentences. Sentencing in individual cases can be subject to appeal.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department has commissioned no external research on the effect of the gender of the judge or the defendant on sentencing outcomes in the Crown Court. However, statistics showing the sentencing outcomes of men and women and also the gender profile of the judiciary are published within the biennial “Statistics on Women and the Criminal Justice System”</p><p>(<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/women-and-the-criminal-justice-system--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/women-and-the-criminal-justice-system--2</a>). The next edition of this publication is due for release in November 2014.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-17T10:15:41.3815345Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77212/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77212/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what research his Department has commissioned on the effect of the gender of (a) the judge and (b) the defendant on sentencing outcomes in Crown Courts.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77213","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-12","<p> </p><p> </p><p>At the end of June we received bids in the competition for the contracts to run the 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies. We have a strong competition in all regions with over 80 bids having been received and an average of four bidders for each area. Over half of the bidders include a voluntary, mutual or social enterprise organisation and mutuals continue to feature strongly, with eight potential staff mutuals competing for a share of the contracts. As well as the Tier 1 provider bids, almost 1000 organisations have registered to play a part in the wider supply chain, including more than 700 listed as VCSE (voluntary, community or social enterprise) organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, charities experienced in tackling a range of issues affecting offenders, small and large businesses and experienced multinationals have partnered together to bid for the work that will help turn offenders’ lives around. All Tier 1 bidders have experience of working with offenders or across the wider Criminal Justice System.</p><p> </p><p>The process to award Community Rehabilitation Company contracts is ongoing and the details of which bidders remain in the competition are commercially sensitive information, which it would not be right to make public at this stage. We are committed to rolling out these important reforms by 2015.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","205038","2014-09-12T15:03:47.3047824Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77213/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77213/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many mutuals have indicated to him that they will bid for work under the Transforming Rehabilitation programme; and how many such organisations have withdrawn from the process.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","205036"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77214","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-17","<p>Arrangements have been put in place, under which self-employed barristers have been instructed to represent defendants in a number of Very High Cost Cases (VHCCs). Given that normal working relationships have been restored, the Government has confirmed that there is no need to expand the PDS further.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-17T14:52:49.7038234Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77214/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77214/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Public Defender Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will publish the agreement recently reached with the Criminal Bar on the future role of the Public Defender Service.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Mr Andy Slaughter","205115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77215","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-21","<p>The information required to provide a full response to the question could not be collated within the timeframe available. I will write to my honourable friend.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-21T14:57:56.3912484Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77215/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77215/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Chris Huhne and Vicky Pryce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what costs his Department incurred in relation to each stage of the judicial proceedings of the cases of (a) Christopher Huhne and (b) Vasiliki Pryce.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","205007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77216","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-09-12","<p> </p><p> </p><p>At the end of June we received bids in the competition for the contracts to run the 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies. We have a strong competition in all regions with over 80 bids having been received and an average of four bidders for each area. Over half of the bidders include a voluntary, mutual or social enterprise organisation and mutuals continue to feature strongly, with eight potential staff mutuals competing for a share of the contracts. As well as the Tier 1 provider bids, almost 1000 organisations have registered to play a part in the wider supply chain, including more than 700 listed as VCSE (voluntary, community or social enterprise) organisations.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to this, charities experienced in tackling a range of issues affecting offenders, small and large businesses and experienced multinationals have partnered together to bid for the work that will help turn offenders’ lives around. All Tier 1 bidders have experience of working with offenders or across the wider Criminal Justice System.</p><p> </p><p>The process to award Community Rehabilitation Company contracts is ongoing and the details of which bidders remain in the competition are commercially sensitive information, which it would not be right to make public at this stage. We are committed to rolling out these important reforms by 2015.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","205036","2014-09-12T15:03:47.4141654Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77216/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77216/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the contracts for work under the Transforming Rehabilitation programme will (a) be signed and (b) become operational.","false","Biography information for Martin Horwood","Cheltenham","Martin Horwood","205038"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77217","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-07-17","<p>Since April 2013 we have undertaken two major public consultations on legal aid, which attracted a large response from the legal professions. In addition, we have spoken at length over the past year with solicitors and barristers and their representatives about the reforms and our final plans reflect many of the changes they asked for.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-07-17T08:40:55.976823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77217/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77217/answer",,,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-07-10","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what consultations he has undertaken with representatives of the legal profession regarding changes to legal aid; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Simon Kirby","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","205019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77218","Leader of the House","false","2014-07-14","<p>The Office of the Leader of the House of Commons is part of the Cabinet Office. Our answer will be included in the response by the Minister for the Cabinet Office, shortly.</p><p> </p>","South Cambridgeshire","Mr Andrew Lansley",,"2014-07-14T13:48:40.6889623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77218/answer","Biography information for Lord Lansley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77218/answer",,,,,,,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, how much and what proportion of his Office's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of his Office's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77219","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-07-15","<p> </p><p>My Department does not hold specific accounting information on activities which were contracted out, and to determine this information would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-07-15T12:30:11.9020572Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77219/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77219/answer",,,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much and what proportion of her Department's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of her Department's budget she expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77220","Northern Ireland Office","false","2014-07-17","<p> </p><p>The Joint Ministerial Task Force on Banking and Access to Finance has formally met twice since its formation and is due to meet again in the autumn. I have also held a number of separate discussions with individual members of the Task Force.</p><p>Significant progress has been made on Task Force priorities to encourage the effective operation of the Business Bank; promote the effectiveness of national finance initiatives; and secure the availability of local bank lending data for Northern Ireland. This data, from the British Bankers' Association, was published for the first time on 2 July alongside the update on the economic pact: <em>Building a Prosperous and United Community: One Year On.</em></p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2014-07-17T15:00:53.6145315Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77220/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77220/answer",,,,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2014-07-10","Banking and Access to Finance Joint Ministerial Task Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many times the Joint Ministerial Task Force on Banking and Access to Finance has met since its formation in 2013; and what actions this body has taken.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","205101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77221","Cabinet Office","false","2014-07-16","<p>My Department outsources with Bouygues, Fujitsu (contracts signed under the previous administration), with the mutual joint venture MyCSP (signed in 2012) and Shared Services Connected Limited (signed in 2013).</p><p>As breakdown by year is</p><p>9/10 £10,370,213</p><p>10/11 £12,567,173</p><p>11/12 £18,417,184</p><p>12/13 £54,189</p><p>13/14 £832,189</p><p>Departmental resource and capital budgets are published online.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Horsham","Mr Francis Maude","204983","2014-07-16T16:53:20.6865556Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77221/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77221/answer",,,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much and what proportion of No. 10 Downing Street's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of No. 10 Downing Street's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77222","Public Accounts Commission","false","2014-07-14","<p>The majority of the NAO's contracted work planned in 2014–15 is in financial audit, where additional audit resources are provided by some half-a-dozen private audit firms. The NAO's partners are chosen through a rigorous process, in line with EU rules on public sector procurement, to ensure value for money. Financial audit work comprises some 55% of the NAO's total activity and around 20% of the NAO's financial audit work is outsourced.</p><p>The use of private firms to carry out some audits is included in the NAO's Strategy, approved by the Public Accounts Commission. The current mix ensures that the NAO maintains the breadth of insight into departments which the C&amp;AG derives on behalf of Parliament from having NAO staff undertake financial audits directly, but also has sufficient exposure to the framework partners so as to benchmark the NAO against the private sector and import best practice. The NAO also uses outsourcing arrangements in its value-for-money or investigations work where specialist skills are required.</p><p><strong>% of NAO Activities contracted out</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Actual</p></td><td><p>Estimate</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td><p>2009–10</p></td><td><p>2010–11</p></td><td><p>2011–12</p></td><td><p>2012–13</p></td><td><p>2013–14</p></td><td><p>2014–15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Professional Services brought in (£ million)</p></td><td><p>17,553</p></td><td><p>13,678</p></td><td><p>13,238</p></td><td><p>11,940</p></td><td><p>10,409</p></td><td><p>10,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Voted Gross Expenditure<br>(Audit and Assurance) (£ million)</p></td><td><p>94,600</p></td><td><p>92,600</p></td><td><p>87,700</p></td><td><p>89,000</p></td><td><p>84,600</p></td><td><p>83,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% of activities contracted out</p></td><td><p>19%</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td><td><p>12%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>Total Voted Gross Expenditure (Audit and Assurance) excludes the following exceptional expenditure:</p><ul><li>Restructuring of the NAO (£4.2m in 2013–14)</li><li>Refurbishment of the NAO building (£16.2 million in 2009–10)</li><li>Temporary accommodation costs (£5.9 million in 2009–10)</li></ul>","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh",,"2014-07-14T16:18:49.9156812Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77222/answer","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77222/answer",,,,,,,,,,"24","Public Accounts Commission","Public Accounts Commission","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chairman of the Public Accounts Commission, how much and what proportion of the National Audit Office's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of the National Audit Office's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77223","Scotland Office","false","2014-07-21","<p>Since its creation in July 1999, the Scotland Office has contracted out work in cleaning, building repairs and maintenance and security guarding. Calculating how much and what proportion of the Office’s budget was spent on these activities in each year between 2009-10 and 2014-15 could only be done by incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2014-07-21T13:02:03.7788142Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77223/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77223/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77223/answer",,,,,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2014-07-10","Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how much and what proportion of his Department's budget was spent on activities which were contracted out in (a) 2009-10, (b) 2010-11, (c) 2011-12, (d) 2012-13 and (e) 2013-14; and how much and what proportion of his Department's budget he expects to be contracted out in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","205225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77224","Speaker's Committee for the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority","false","2014-09-11","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority. I have asked IPSA to reply.</p><p> </p><p><em>Letter from Marcial Boo, July 2014:</em></p><p> </p><p>As Chief Executive of the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority, I have been asked to reply to your Parliamentary Question asking about contracted out services.</p><p> </p><p>Contracted out expenditure has been interpreted as all third party expenditure and the data are set out in the below table.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Costs (£'000)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td> </td><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Actual</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Forecast</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Financial year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009-2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010-2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011-2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012-2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013-2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014-2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Costs</strong></p></td><td><p>1650</p></td><td><p>3332</p></td><td><p>946</p></td><td><p>1406</p></td><td><p>1646</p></td><td><p>1709.535</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>IPSA's administrative budget</strong></p></td><td><p>4448</p></td><td><p>10394</p></td><td><p>8364</p></td><td><p>7908</p></td><td><p>10152</p></td><td><p>10332</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>% of budget related to contracted out services</strong></p></td><td><p>37%</p></td><td><p>32%</p></td><td><p>11%</p></td><td><p>18%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>17%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Broxbourne","Mr Charles Walker",,"2014-09-11T15:52:14.2340324Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77224/answer","Biography information for Sir Charles Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/77224/answer",